1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,559
degree from a leading New York university.

2
00:00:02,750 --> 00:00:05,440
How did he spend his three years in the Army?

3
00:00:05,550 --> 00:00:06,960
Not as an officer.

4
00:00:07,069 --> 00:00:09,040
Not as a staff specialist.

5
00:00:09,230 --> 00:00:12,400
Instead, for three years, he drove a truck.

6
00:00:12,750 --> 00:00:13,359
Why?

7
00:00:13,630 --> 00:00:17,760
Because he was filled with negative attitudes toward fellow soldiers.

8
00:00:17,950 --> 00:00:19,599
I'm superior to them.

9
00:00:19,870 --> 00:00:22,319
Toward Army methods and procedures.

10
00:00:22,430 --> 00:00:23,599
They are stupid.

11
00:00:23,870 --> 00:00:25,200
Toward discipline?

12
00:00:25,309 --> 00:00:27,200
It's for others, not me.

13
00:00:27,550 --> 00:00:30,400
Toward everything, including himself.

14
00:00:30,670 --> 00:00:34,559
I'm a fool for not figuring out a way to escape this wrap.

15
00:00:35,150 --> 00:00:37,920
This fellow earned no respect from anyone.

16
00:00:38,110 --> 00:00:41,200
All his vast store of knowledge lay buried.

17
00:00:41,390 --> 00:00:44,720
His negative attitudes turned him into a flunky.

18
00:00:45,390 --> 00:00:52,559
Remember, the thinking that guides your intelligence is much more important than how much intelligence you have.

19
00:00:52,910 --> 00:00:54,480
Not even a Ph.D.

20
00:00:54,510 --> 00:00:58,559
degree can override this basic success principle.

21
00:00:59,309 --> 00:01:07,280
Several years ago, I became a close friend of Phil F., one of the senior officers of a major advertising agency.

22
00:01:07,630 --> 00:01:13,280
Phil was director of marketing research for the agency, and he was doing a bang-up job.

23
00:01:13,710 --> 00:01:15,520
Was Phil a brain?

24
00:01:15,710 --> 00:01:16,720
Far from it.

25
00:01:16,910 --> 00:01:20,160
Phil knew next to nothing about research technique.

26
00:01:20,350 --> 00:01:22,800
He knew next to nothing about statistics.

27
00:01:22,990 --> 00:01:27,119
He was not a college graduate, though all the people working for him were.

28
00:01:27,230 --> 00:01:31,440
And Phil did not pretend to know the technical side of research.

29
00:01:31,870 --> 00:01:39,920
What then enabled Phil to command $30,000 a year while not one of his subordinates earned $10,000?

30
00:01:40,670 --> 00:01:41,280
This.

31
00:01:41,870 --> 00:01:44,400
Phil was a human engineer.

32
00:01:44,670 --> 00:01:47,359
Phil was 100% positive.

33
00:01:47,550 --> 00:01:50,559
Phil could inspire others when they felt low.

34
00:01:50,670 --> 00:01:52,800
Phil was enthusiastic.

35
00:01:52,910 --> 00:01:55,040
He generated enthusiasm.

36
00:01:55,230 --> 00:01:57,119
Phil understood people.

37
00:01:57,150 --> 00:02:01,040
And because he could really see what made them tick, he liked them.

38
00:02:01,550 --> 00:02:12,000
Not Phil's brains, but how he managed those brains made him three times more valuable to his company than men who rated higher on the IQ scale.

39
00:02:12,430 --> 00:02:18,000
Out of every 100 persons who enroll in college, fewer than 50 will graduate.

40
00:02:18,190 --> 00:02:24,800
I was curious about this, so I asked a director of admissions at a large university for his explanation.

41
00:02:25,309 --> 00:02:28,240
It's not insufficient intelligence, he said.

42
00:02:28,430 --> 00:02:31,520
We don't admit them if they don't have sufficient ability.

43
00:02:31,710 --> 00:02:33,200
And it's not money.

44
00:02:33,390 --> 00:02:37,440
Anyone who wants to support himself in college today can do so.

45
00:02:37,710 --> 00:02:39,839
The real reason is attitudes.

46
00:02:40,030 --> 00:02:46,559
You would be surprised, he said, how many young people leave because they don't like their professors,

47
00:02:46,589 --> 00:02:50,000
the subjects they must take, and their fellow students.

48
00:02:50,589 --> 00:03:00,319
The same reason, negative thinking, explains why the door to top-flight executive positions is closed to many young junior executives.

49
00:03:00,670 --> 00:03:09,680
Sour, negative, pessimistic, depreciating attitudes, rather than insufficient intelligence, hold back thousands of young executives.

50
00:03:10,030 --> 00:03:16,800
As one executive told me, it's a rare case when we pass up a young fellow because he lacks brains.

51
00:03:16,990 --> 00:03:19,440
Nearly always it's attitude.

52
00:03:20,030 --> 00:03:29,520
Once, I was retained by an insurance company to learn why the top 25% of the agents were selling over 75% of the insurance,

53
00:03:29,550 --> 00:03:35,359
while the bottom 25% of the agents sold only 5% of total volume.

54
00:03:35,790 --> 00:03:39,119
Thousands of personnel files were carefully checked.

55
00:03:39,230 --> 00:03:46,079
The search proved beyond any question that no significant difference existed in native intelligence.

56
00:03:46,350 --> 00:03:52,079
What's more, differences in education did not explain the difference in selling success.

57
00:03:52,510 --> 00:04:02,559
The difference in the very successful and the very unsuccessful finally reduced to differences in attitudes or difference in thought management.

58
00:04:02,829 --> 00:04:08,720
The top group worried less, was more enthusiastic, had a sincere liking for people.

